{
  "situations": [
    {
      "dialogue": "I am designing a game spinner with four sections: 1, 2, 3, and a double-sized wedge for 4. I listed the sample space as `S = {1, 2, 3, 4, 4}` so the extra chance for 4 is obvious in my set.",
      "imagePrompt": "A colorful circular board game spinner divided into sections labeled 1, 2, 3, and a double-wide section labeled 4, with a handwritten notepad nearby showing the set S = {1, 2, 3, 4, 4}.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Correct! A sample space must list each unique outcome exactly once. To account for the double-sized wedge, we use probabilities (like weight or area), not duplicate elements in the sample space.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "List 4 only once"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Keeping both elements violates the rule that sample space outcomes must be distinct, which will mess up standard probability formulas.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Keep both 4s"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "This groups distinct numbers together and does not solve the fundamental issue of how to represent the individual outcomes on the spinner.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Group them as odd or even"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Adding a new number like 8 introduces an outcome that is physically impossible on this spinner.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Replace the duplicate with 8"
        }
      ],
      "question": "How should you correct this sample space list to ensure every possible outcome is listed exactly once?"
    },
    {
      "dialogue": "I am testing an automated coin-flipper that tosses a coin twice in a row. I defined our sample space as `S = {HH, TT, HT}` since those are the combinations I see on my summary sheet.",
      "imagePrompt": "An automated testing rig with two shiny silver coins lying on a blue surface, one showing Heads and one showing Tails, next to a clipboard showing the list S = {HH, TT, HT}.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Correct! Flipping Tails first then Heads (TH) is a distinct, separate outcome from flipping Heads first then Tails (HT). The current list is missing this outcome.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Add the missing outcome TH"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "None of the outcomes listed (HH, TT, HT) are duplicates; they are all unique combinations.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Remove HT to avoid duplicates"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Single flips like H and T are outcomes for a single toss, but this trial consists of two consecutive tosses.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Change it to single tosses"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The order of the flips matters for defining distinct physical paths, so we cannot combine them into a single three-element set.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Combine them into a single flip"
        }
      ],
      "question": "What is wrong with this sample space list for a two-flip trial?"
    },
    {
      "dialogue": "{{NAME}}, I'm setting up a raffle wheel with numbers 1 through 10. To make things simpler for the prize categories, I listed my base sample space as `S = {Even, Odd, Multiple of 5}`.",
      "imagePrompt": "A large wooden prize wheel painted with numbers from 1 to 10, next to a whiteboard on an easel displaying the text S = {Even, Odd, Multiple of 5}.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Correct! A standard sample space must consist of mutually exclusive outcomes. Here, the number 10 is both 'Even' and a 'Multiple of 5', meaning these categories overlap.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "The outcomes overlap"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "While 10 is indeed even and a multiple of 5, the issue is that the categories themselves overlap, not that the list is incomplete.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The number 10 is missing"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Each of the three category labels appears exactly once in the list; there are no duplicate words.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The list duplicates Odd"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The labels themselves do not have to be raw numbers, but they must describe mutually exclusive outcomes, which these do not.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The labels are text words"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Why is this set invalid as a basic sample space of mutually exclusive outcomes?"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "situations": [
    {
      "dialogue": "Look at this plastic yellow duck sitting on the pond, {{NAME}}. I just threw a stone in the water, and a series of ripples is traveling outward across the pond. The duck is about to meet the first wave crest.",
      "imagePrompt": "A yellow rubber duck floating on calm pond water with circular ripples approaching it from a distance.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Correct! The water particles (the medium) only oscillate locally up and down as the disturbance passes. The duck, floating on the water, bobs with it but does not travel with the wave.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Bob up and down in its spot"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Incorrect. While it looks like water moves forward, only the wave energy/disturbance propagates. The water molecules (and the duck) only oscillate locally.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Ride the crest to the shore"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Incorrect. The wave doesn't pull the floating object down; it temporarily lifts and lowers it as the crest and trough pass.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Sink down to the bottom"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Incorrect. The passing wave primarily moves the water vertically or in small local orbits, causing a bobbing motion, not continuous spinning.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Spin rapidly in a circle"
        }
      ],
      "question": "How will the duck move as the wave passes its position?"
    },
    {
      "dialogue": "We placed a lit candle right in front of a loud subwoofer playing a deep, continuous bass note. We can see the flame flickering, but it doesn't get blown out like it would by a steady breeze.",
      "imagePrompt": "A close-up of a large audio speaker cone vibrating next to a lit candle flame which is flickering back and forth.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Correct! Sound is a longitudinal mechanical wave. The air molecules oscillate back and forth about their equilibrium positions, passing the energy along without traveling forward as wind.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Air oscillates locally without flowing forward"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Incorrect. If air molecules were continuously shot out, that would be wind (bulk transport of matter). Mechanical waves only cause local oscillations of the medium.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Air molecules shoot out like wind"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Incorrect. Although there are temporary regions of lower pressure (rarefactions), they alternate rapidly with high-pressure regions (compressions) and do not create a permanent vacuum pulling air.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "A permanent vacuum is created"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Incorrect. While sound can travel through solids like wax, the wave shaking the flame is traveling through the surrounding air.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The wave travels through the wax"
        }
      ],
      "question": "What does this tell us about how the sound wave travels through the air?"
    },
    {
      "dialogue": "After the minor tremor passed, we checked the geophone data and looked at this row of wooden fence posts. During the tremor, the posts swayed side-to-side, but they are still anchored in their original post holes.",
      "imagePrompt": "A row of old wooden fence posts in a grassy field during an earthquake tremor, with motion blur indicating a side-to-side shaking of the ground.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Correct! The ground/rock is the medium. The mechanical seismic wave is a disturbance that travels through the earth, while the earth itself (and the posts in it) only oscillates locally.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "The ground only shook locally"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Incorrect. Seismic waves are mechanical waves, meaning they absolutely require a physical medium (the ground) to travel.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Seismic waves need no medium"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Incorrect. If the first post absorbed all the energy, the tremor wouldn't have propagated past it to shake the other posts.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The first post absorbed all energy"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Incorrect. If the ground moved permanently with the wave, the earth's crust would be rapidly shifting miles away with every tremor. The medium only oscillates.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The ground migrated with the wave"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Which of the following best explains why the fence posts remained in place after the wave passed?"
    },
    {
      "dialogue": "We tied a bright red ribbon to a single metal coil in the middle of this stretched slinky. Now, we are sending a sharp push-and-pull wave pulse down the spring from one end to the other.",
      "imagePrompt": "A silver metal slinky stretched out on a blue table with a single red ribbon tied to one coil in the center. A hand is about to push the end to create a longitudinal wave.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Correct! The ribbon marks a single part of the medium (the spring). As the longitudinal wave passes, that part oscillates back and forth parallel to the wave direction, then returns to its equilibrium position.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Shift forward and backward locally"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Incorrect. The wave disturbance travels to the end, but the physical coils of the spring do not. They only oscillate locally.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Slide to the far end"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Incorrect. This is a push-and-pull (longitudinal) pulse, so the motion is back-and-forth along the spring's axis, not up-and-down.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Wave in a high vertical arch"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Incorrect. The wave is a disturbance of the medium itself; the ribbon must move because the coil it is tied to must oscillate to pass the wave along.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Remain completely motionless"
        }
      ],
      "question": "As the longitudinal pulse passes through the center of the slinky, how will the red ribbon behave?"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "situations": [
    {
      "dialogue": "Veja, {{NAME}}, nós temos a dotação orçamentária aprovada na LOA para a reforma da escola. Mas a Secretaria de Finanças diz que não podemos liberar o edital ainda porque a arrecadação caiu e o caixa está vazio. O que está faltando aqui?",
      "imagePrompt": "An office table with a colorful municipal budget booklet showing Dotação: R$ 500.000 highlighted, alongside a computer screen showing a bank balance of R$ 0,00 with a warning sign.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Exato! Ter dotação orçamentária (crédito) significa apenas que a lei autoriza o gasto. Sem o fluxo financeiro correspondente (dinheiro em caixa), a despesa não pode ser executada.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Falta de fluxo financeiro"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Incorreto. A autorização legislativa já existe na LOA por meio da dotação orçamentária. O problema atual é a falta de dinheiro real na conta do Tesouro.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Falta de autorização legislativa"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Incorreto. A liquidação é uma etapa posterior do processo de despesa, que ocorre somente após a entrega do serviço contratado.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Falta de liquidação patrimonial"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Incorreto. A receita foi prevista legalmente, mas a arrecadação real de impostos ficou abaixo do esperado, frustrando o caixa.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Inexistência de receita prevista"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Qual é a distinção financeira fundamental que está impedindo o início da reforma?"
    },
    {
      "dialogue": "Os novos notebooks para a defensoria acabaram de chegar em caixas fechadas. O fornecedor quer receber o pagamento imediatamente, alegando que o empenho já foi feito mês passado. O que devemos fazer antes de transferir o dinheiro?",
      "imagePrompt": "A warehouse floor with stacks of sealed cardboard boxes containing laptops. A public servant holds a clipboard, examining a checklist labeled Termo de Recebimento.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Perfeito! A liquidação é o estágio em que a administração pública verifica o direito adquirido do credor, certificando que o objeto foi de fato entregue conforme as especificações contratadas.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Realizar a liquidação"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Incorreto. O empenho já foi realizado anteriormente para reservar o orçamento. Repetir esta etapa não atesta que as mercadorias de fato chegaram.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Emitir um novo empenho"
